\subsection{Microstrip Antenna as EM Field Sensor}\label{LR_Microstrip_antenna_sensor}\index{EM field sensor!microstrip antenna} 
Microstrip antenna has been one of the most innovative topics in antenna theory and design, and is increasingly finding applications in a wide range of modern microwave systems. To a large extent, the development of microstrip antenna has been driven by system requirements for antennas with low profile, low weight, low cost, easy integrability into arrays or into microwave integrated circuits and for polarization diversity. The microstrip antenna configuration easily satisfies all the above requirements. Another interesting feature is that microstrip antennas can be fabricated rather easily in university or other research laboratories, which have often been a source of novel designs. The work by Bailey and Aggarwal \cite{Agrawal_analysis_technique_for_microstrip_antennas_conf}, \cite{Agrawal_analysis_technique_for_microstrip_antennas} can be considered as an introductory work on analytical methods for analysis of microstrip structures. The transmission line model for the microstrip proposed by Derneryd \cite{Derneryd_heoretical_investigation_rectangular_microstrip_antenna}, \cite{Derneryd_Extended_analysis__microstrip_resonator_antennas}, was successful in predicting the input impedance approximately. The review papers by Carver $et~al.$ \cite{Carver_Microstrip_antenna_technology} and Richards $et~al.$ \cite{Richards_improved_theory_microstrip_antennas_applications}, provide a good insight into the early stages of development of microstrip technology. The FDTD method has applied to the full-wave analysis of various microstrip structures in \cite{Ali_planar_microstrip_circuits}. The method is shown to be an efficient tool for modeling complicated microstrip circuit components as well as microstrip antennas.


The application of microstrip antennas in the field of EMI/EMC, specifically as an EMFS requires the knowledge of microstrip antenna characteristics in receiving mode.

 
